  <div class="friendReviews elementListBrown" >
    <div class="section">
      

<div id="review_1243831009" class="review nosyndicate" itemprop="reviews" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Review">
  <link itemprop="url" href="https://www.goodreads.com/review/show/1243831009" />
    <a title="Karla" class="left imgcol" href="/user/show/2846441-karla"><img alt="Karla" src="https://images.gr-assets.com/users/1537371209p2/2846441.jpg" /></a>

  <div class="left bodycol">
    <div class="reviewHeader uitext stacked">
        <a class="reviewDate createdAt right" href="/review/show/1243831009?book_show_action=true">Apr 02, 2015</a>

      <span itemprop="author" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Person">
        <a title="Karla" class="user" itemprop="url" name="Karla" href="/user/show/2846441-karla">Karla</a>
      </span>

        rated it
        <span class=" staticStars notranslate" title="it was amazing"><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10">it was amazing</span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span></span>



        

          <div class="uitext greyText bookshelves">
            Shelves:
              <a class="actionLinkLite" href="/review/list/2846441-karla?shelf=ebook">ebook</a>
          </div>
    </div>


        <div class="reviewText stacked">
              <span id="reviewTextContainer1243831009" class="readable"
              >
            
<span id="freeTextContainer15261030064255410699">Dear Lawrence Wright,<br/><br/><img src='https://images.gr-assets.com/hostedimages/1428931334ra/14502193.gif' class='gr-hostedUserImg'/><br/><br/>Sincerely,<br/>Me<br/><br/>* * *<br/><br/>I&apos;m finding it impossible to organize the hundreds of thoughts I have about this book.<br/><br/>The only regret I have is that it could have been far more comprehensive...if That Authoritarian Cult had a cooperative bone in its twisted little body. But cooperation and &quot;shadowy, secretive cult&quot; are incompatible concepts. If David Miscavige hates Wright&apos;s end product, he had it within his power to cooperate because, if anything, Wright shows a willingness to be fair and</span>
  <span id="freeText15261030064255410699" style="display:none">Dear Lawrence Wright,<br><br><img src="https://images.gr-assets.com/hostedimages/1428931334ra/14502193.gif" class="gr-hostedUserImg"><br><br>Sincerely,<br>Me<br><br>* * *<br><br>I'm finding it impossible to organize the hundreds of thoughts I have about this book.<br><br>The only regret I have is that it could have been far more comprehensive...if That Authoritarian Cult had a cooperative bone in its twisted little body. But cooperation and "shadowy, secretive cult" are incompatible concepts. If David Miscavige hates Wright's end product, he had it within his power to cooperate because, if anything, Wright shows a willingness to be fair and even-handed - and he even professes an admiration for L. Ron Hubbard as a motivated thinker, creative confabulator, and cagey pitchman.<br><br>The history of Hubbard's punitively-based pseudoscience is utterly fascinating for its insight into the human psyche. There's the <b>longing to be elite</b>, which is fellated by the earth-shattering revealed secrets as one moves up the various OT levels; the <b>bottomless capacity for gullibility</b>, as a fantastically outrageous origin myth is either swallowed whole or compartmentalized by nagging skepticism, while still gladly handing over wads of cash on a regular basis (or working for near-slave wages); the <b>submission to the authoritarian personality</b>, as the organization's cogs identify with those who use and abuse them, willingly assuming the guilt for whatever failures are laid on their shoulders by those in charge.<br><br>It seems like there is sometimes such a thing as a "cafeteria Scientologist," but the organization's tentacles still manage to get a grip and it takes a very long time to extract oneself from the mire. This is what the Paul Haggis narrative that extends throughout the entire book felt like to me. He's poised as the anti-Tom Cruise, a Hollywood celeb who considered himself a good and loyal member, but still had his feet on the ground and his conscience unblinded by the trappings of groveling courtship by Miscavige (who really comes across as a manipulative starfucker). Given the intensity of retribution that LRH/Miscavige had no compunctions about unleashing on any critics (including the IRS), Haggis' unwavering apostasy while remaining in the geographic belly of the beast is even more admirable.<br><br>One of the unexpected highlights of the book were the footnootes. Never have I seen such a concentrated collection of denials, disclaimers, and do-not-recalls through attorney mouthpieces. From Miscavige to Travolta to Cruise to even Spielberg, it's a steady stream of:<br><br><img src="https://images.gr-assets.com/hostedimages/1429023980ra/14516960.gif" class="gr-hostedUserImg"><br><br>Who knows if this book - and the recent higher profile via the Alex Gibney documentary on HBO - is going to inflict lasting damage on Hubbard's money-making scam. I hope it does, but the human capacity to ignore reality and cling to marginalized martyrdom is a formidable opponent. It's the foundation on which the "church" was built and the aura of an unfairly maligned, enlightened, and destined-for-greatness super elite still powers it today.<br><br>Oh, and cash. Millions of buckets of that.<br><br>Even though I've been more than passing familiar with a lot of the dark stories surrounding Scientology, Wright's exposé admirably collected it all together in a coherent, elucidating narrative. I ended this book with the image of self-help via motorized hamster wheel: There is no getting off, no end point, and pretty soon its the hamster's imposed reality. It was a revelation.<br><br><img src="https://images.gr-assets.com/hostedimages/1428930840ra/14502137.gif" class="gr-hostedUserImg"></span>
  <a data-text-id="15261030064255410699" href="#" onclick="swapContent($(this));; return false;">...more</a>

          </span>
        </div>


      <div class="reviewFooter uitext buttons">
          

